;; 04-where-to-write-user-data.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 4

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   4
  :title            "Where To Write User Data"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"User data is the material the user has said they want kept. Cortex
entries. SLAT files the user asked the Copilot to save. Artifacts
the Copilot produced on the user's behalf and the user chose to
retain. This chapter is about where those files land.

The rule under every choice: user data belongs to the app's own
private, backed-up area. Not the shared filesystem. Not a temp
directory. Not a cache. The place the OS backs up and syncs.

Per host, the honest answer is:

- `phone-ios`, `tablet-ipad`:
  `~/Documents/` inside the app's sandbox. This is the area iOS
  backs up to iCloud when the user has iCloud backup on. It is
  visible to the user via the Files app if the Info.plist declares
  `UIFileSharingEnabled`, otherwise private. Either way, this is
  where user data goes.

- `phone-android`, `tablet-android`:
  `getFilesDir()` inside the app's private data area. On modern
  Android this is under `/data/data/<package>/files/` and is
  private to the app. If the user has enabled auto-backup the OS
  will back it up.

- `computer-macos`:
  `~/Library/Application Support/<AppName>/` for private data,
  or `~/Documents/<AppName>/` for user-facing files. Motoi
  Copilot prefers Application Support for cortex and internal
  state; it uses Documents only when the user has explicitly
  asked for a file they will want to open by hand.

- `computer-linux`:
  `${XDG_DATA_HOME:-~/.local/share}/<AppName>/`. This is the
  XDG-defined location for durable app data. Never dump into
  `~` at root.

- `computer-windows`:
  `%APPDATA%\\<AppName>\\` — this resolves to something like
  `C:\\Users\\<user>\\AppData\\Roaming\\<AppName>\\`. The Roaming
  variant syncs across the user's Windows profiles; the Local
  variant does not.

- `unknown`:
  The current working directory, in a subdirectory the Copilot
  creates on first write: `./motoi-data/`. Conservative default.

The Copilot does not compute these paths itself. The host injects
them. The environment variable convention is `MOTOI_DATA_DIR`. If
set, use it. If unset, fall back to `MOTOI_HOST` and choose a
per-host default in application code.

Read pattern:

```scheme
(define (motoi/data-dir)
  (or (get-environment-variable \"MOTOI_DATA_DIR\")
      \"./motoi-data\"))
```

The Copilot then composes paths under that directory by simple
string append. It never assumes a separator that isn't a forward
slash — see Chapter 8 on path conventions.

```scheme
(define (motoi/cortex-path)
  (string-append (motoi/data-dir) \"/cortex.slat\"))

(display (motoi/cortex-path)) (newline)
```

Cortex is the Copilot's memory. It is user data. It goes here. On
a phone that means it will be backed up; on a laptop it means it
will survive a reinstall of the app; on `unknown` it means it
sits next to the working directory and the user can move it by
hand.

One more discipline: the Copilot does not create the data
directory as a side effect of a random call. It creates it on the
first write, and it wraps that first write in a small transaction:
write to a temp name, fsync, rename. That way a crashed process
does not leave a half-file where a cortex should be. The runtime
does not have `fsync` verbs of its own — the host provides them
through the SLAT write layer. Trust the layer; do not fake it.")
